[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] In both contexts it refers to simplifying a complicated problem by breaking it down into simpler sub-problems in a recursive manner.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] While some decision problems cannot be taken apart this way, decisions that span several points in time do often break apart recursively.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Likewise, in computer science, if a problem can be solved optimally by breaking it into sub-problems and then recursively finding the optimal solutions to the sub-problems, then it is said to have *optimal substructure*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] If sub-problems can be nested recursively inside larger problems, so that dynamic programming methods are applicable, then there is a relation between the value of the larger problem and the values of the sub-problems.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] In the optimization literature this relationship is called the Bellman equation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] In terms of mathematical optimization, dynamic programming usually refers to simplifying a decision by breaking it down into a sequence of decision steps over time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] This is done by defining a sequence of **value functions** *V*1, *V*2, ..., *V**n* taking *y* as an argument representing the **state** of the system at times *i* from 1 to *n*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The definition of *V**n*(*y*) is the value obtained in state *y* at the last time *n*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The values *V**i* at earlier times *i* = *n* −1, *n* − 2, ..., 2, 1 can be found by working backwards, using a recursive relationship called the Bellman equation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] For *i* = 2, ..., *n*, *V**i*−1 at any state *y* is calculated from *V**i* by maximizing a simple function (usually the sum) of the gain from a decision at time *i* − 1 and the function *V**i* at the new state of the system if this decision is made.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Since *V**i* has already been calculated for the needed states, the above operation yields *V**i*−1 for those states.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Finally, *V*1 at the initial state of the system is the value of the optimal solution.
