[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] There are many options because matrix multiplication is associative.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] In other words, no matter how the product is parenthesized, the result obtained will remain the same.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Although it does not affect the product, the order in which the terms are parenthesized affects the number of simple arithmetic operations needed to compute the product, that is, the computational complexity.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The straightforward multiplication of a matrix that is *X* × *Y* by a matrix that is *Y* × *Z* requires *XYZ* ordinary multiplications and *X*(*Y* − 1)*Z* ordinary additions.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] In this context, it is typical to use the number of ordinary multiplications as a measure of the runtime complexity.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Clearly the first method is more efficient.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] A quicker solution to this problem can be achieved by breaking up the problem into a set of related subproblems.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] To begin, let us assume that all we really want to know is the minimum cost, or minimum number of arithmetic operations needed to multiply out the matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] If we are only multiplying two matrices, there is only one way to multiply them, so the minimum cost is the cost of doing this.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] For example, if we have four matrices *ABCD*, we compute the cost required to find each of (*A*)(*BCD*), (*AB*)(*CD*), and (*ABC*)(*D*), making recursive calls to find the minimum cost to compute *ABC*, *AB*, *CD*, and *BCD*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Better still, this yields not only the minimum cost, but also demonstrates the best way of doing the multiplication: group it the way that yields the lowest total cost, and do the same for each factor.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] However, this algorithm has exponential runtime complexity making it as inefficient as the naive approach of trying all permutations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The reason is that the algorithm does a lot of redundant work.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] For example, above we made a recursive call to find the best cost for computing both *ABC* and *AB*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] But finding the best cost for computing ABC also requires finding the best cost for *AB*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] As the recursion grows deeper, more and more of this type of unnecessary repetition occurs.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] One simple solution is called memoization: each time we compute the minimum cost needed to multiply out a specific subsequence, we save it.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] If we are ever asked to compute it again, we simply give the saved answer, and do not recompute it.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Since there are about *n*2/2 different subsequences, where *n* is the number of matrices, the space required to do this is reasonable.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] It can be shown that this simple trick brings the runtime down to O(*n*3) from exponential, which is more than efficient enough for real applications.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The following bottom-up approach computes, for each 2 ≤ *k* ≤ n, the minimum costs of all subsequences of length *k* using the costs of smaller subsequences already computed.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] It has the same asymptotic runtime and requires no recursion.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] There are algorithms that are more efficient than the *O*(*n*3) dynamic programming algorithm, though they are more complex.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Shing achieves *O*(*n* log *n*) computational complexity.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] They showed how the matrix chain multiplication problem can be transformed (or reduced) into the problem of triangulation of a regular polygon.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The polygon is oriented such that there is a horizontal bottom side, called the base, which represents the final result.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The other *n* sides of the polygon, in the clockwise direction, represent the matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The vertices on each end of a side are the dimensions of the matrix represented by that side.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] With *n* matrices in the multiplication chain there are *n*−1 binary operations and *C**n*−1 ways of placing parentheses, where *C**n*−1 is the (*n*−1)-th Catalan number.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The algorithm exploits that there are also *C**n*−1 possible triangulations of a polygon with *n*+1 sides.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] This image illustrates possible triangulations of a regular hexagon.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] These correspond to the different ways that parentheses can be placed to order the multiplications for a product of 5 matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] For the example below, there are four sides: A, B, C and the final result ABC.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] A is a 10×30 matrix, B is a 30×5 matrix, C is a 5×60 matrix, and the final result is a 10×60 matrix.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The matrix product AB is a 10x5 matrix and BC is a 30x60 matrix.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The cost of a single triangle in terms of the number of multiplications needed is the product of its vertices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Hu & Shing developed an algorithm that finds an optimum solution for the minimum cost partition problem in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Their proof of correctness of the algorithm relies on "Lemma 1" proved in a 1981 technical report and omitted from the published paper.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The technical report's proof of the lemma is incorrect, but Shing has presented a corrected proof.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Wang, Zhu and Tian have published a simplified *O*(*n* log *m*) algorithm, where *n* is the number of matrices in the chain and *m* is the number of local minimums in the dimension sequence of the given matrix chain.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] An algorithm created independently by Chin and Hu & Shing runs in O(*n*) and produces a parenthesization which is at most 15.47% worse than the optimal choice.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] In most cases the algorithm yields the optimal solution or a solution which is only 1-2 percent worse than the optimal one.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] The algorithm starts by translating the problem to the polygon partitioning problem.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] To each vertex *V* of the polygon is associated a weight *w*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Suppose we have three consecutive vertices $V_{i-1},V_{i},V_{i+1}$ , and that $V_{\min }$ is the vertex with minimum weight $w_{\min }$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] We look at the quadrilateral with vertices $V_{\min },V_{i-1},V_{i},V_{i+1}$ (in clockwise order).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] we remove the vertex $V_{i}$ from the polygon and add the side $(V_{i-1},V_{i+1})$ to the triangulation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] We repeat this process until no $V_{i}$ satisfies the condition above.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] For all the remaining vertices $V_{n}$ , we add the side $(V_{\min },V_{n})$ to the triangulation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] This gives us a nearly optimal triangulation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] A practical instance of this comes from the ordering of join operations in databases; see Query optimization § Join ordering.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Another somewhat contrived special case of this is string concatenation of a list of strings.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] In C, for example, the cost of concatenating two strings of length *m* and *n* using *strcat* is O(*m* + *n*), since we need O(*m*) time to find the end of the first string and O(*n*) time to copy the second string onto the end of it.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Using this cost function, we can write a dynamic programming algorithm to find the fastest way to concatenate a sequence of strings.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] However, this optimization is rather useless because we can straightforwardly concatenate the strings in time proportional to the sum of their lengths.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] A similar problem exists for singly linked lists.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] Another generalization is to solve the problem when parallel processors are available.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] In this case, instead of adding the costs of computing each factor of a matrix product, we take the maximum because we can do them simultaneously.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] This can drastically affect both the minimum cost and the final optimal grouping; more "balanced" groupings that keep all the processors busy are favored.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-chain-multiplication] There are even more sophisticated approaches.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Because matrix multiplication is such a central operation in many numerical algorithms, much work has been invested in making **matrix multiplication algorithms** efficient.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Applications of matrix multiplication in computational problems are found in many fields including scientific computing and pattern recognition and in seemingly unrelated problems such as counting the paths through a graph.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Many different algorithms have been designed for multiplying matrices on different types of hardware, including parallel and distributed systems, where the computational work is spread over multiple processors (perhaps over a network).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Directly applying the mathematical definition of matrix multiplication gives an algorithm that takes time on the order of *n*3 field operations to multiply two *n* × *n* matrices over that field (Θ(*n*3) in big O notation).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Better asymptotic bounds on the time required to multiply matrices have been known since the Strassen's algorithm in the 1960s, but the optimal time (that is, the computational complexity of matrix multiplication) remains unknown.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] As of September 2025, the best bound on the asymptotic complexity of a matrix multiplication algorithm is O(*n*2.371339) time, given by Alman, Duan, Williams, Xu, Xu, and Zhou.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] However, this algorithm is a galactic algorithm because of the large constants and cannot be realized practically.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This algorithm takes time Θ(*nmp*) (in asymptotic notation).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] A common simplification for the purpose of algorithm analysis is to assume that the inputs are all square matrices of size *n* × *n*, in which case the running time is Θ(*n*3), i.e., cubic in the size of the dimension.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The three loops in iterative matrix multiplication can be arbitrarily swapped with each other without an effect on correctness or asymptotic running time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] However, the order can have a considerable impact on practical performance due to the memory access patterns and cache use of the algorithm; which order is best also depends on whether the matrices are stored in row-major order, column-major order, or a mix of both.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] In particular, in the idealized case of a fully associative cache consisting of M bytes and b bytes per cache line (i.e. ⁠*M*/*b*⁠ cache lines), the above algorithm is sub-optimal for A and B stored in row-major order.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] When *n* > ⁠*M*/*b*⁠, every iteration of the inner loop (a simultaneous sweep through a row of A and a column of B) incurs a cache miss when accessing an element of B.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This means that the algorithm incurs Θ(*n*3) cache misses in the worst case.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] As of 2010, the speed of memories compared to that of processors is such that the cache misses, rather than the actual calculations, dominate the running time for sizable matrices.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] In the idealized cache model, this algorithm incurs only Θ(⁠*n*3/*b* √*M*⁠) cache misses; the divisor *b* √*M* amounts to several orders of magnitude on modern machines, so that the actual calculations dominate the running time, rather than the cache misses.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] An alternative to the iterative algorithm is the divide-and-conquer algorithm for matrix multiplication.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] which works for all square matrices whose dimensions are powers of two, i.e., the shapes are 2*n* × 2*n* for some n.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] which consists of eight multiplications of pairs of submatrices, followed by an addition step.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer algorithm computes the smaller multiplications recursively, using the scalar multiplication *c*11 = *a*11*b*11 as its base case.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] accounting for the eight recursive calls on matrices of size *n*/2 and Θ(*n*2) to sum the four pairs of resulting matrices element-wise.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Application of the master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences shows this recursion to have the solution Θ(*n*3), the same as the iterative algorithm.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] A variant of this algorithm that works for matrices of arbitrary shapes and is faster in practice splits matrices in two instead of four submatrices, as follows.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Splitting a matrix now means dividing it into two parts of equal size, or as close to equal sizes as possible in the case of odd dimensions.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Algorithms exist that provide better running times than the straightforward ones.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The first to be discovered was Strassen's algorithm, devised by Volker Strassen in 1969 and often referred to as "fast matrix multiplication".
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] It is based on a way of multiplying two 2×2 matrices which requires only 7 multiplications (instead of the usual 8), at the expense of several additional addition and subtraction operations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Applying this recursively gives an algorithm with a multiplicative cost of $O(n^{\log _{2}7})\approx O(n^{2.807})$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Strassen's algorithm is more complex, and the numerical stability is reduced compared to the naïve algorithm, but it is faster in cases where *n* > 100 or so and appears in several libraries, such as BLAS.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] It is very useful for large matrices over exact domains such as finite fields, where numerical stability is not an issue.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Since Strassen's algorithm is actually used in practical numerical software and computer algebra systems, improving on the constants hidden in the big-O notation has its merits.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] A table that compares key aspects of the improved version based on recursive multiplication of 2×2-block matrices via 7 block matrix multiplications follows.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] As usual, n gives the dimensions of the matrix and M designates the memory size.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] It is known that a Strassen-like algorithm with a 2×2-block matrix step requires at least 7 block matrix multiplications.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] In 1976 Probert showed that such an algorithm requires at least 15 additions (including subtractions); however, a hidden assumption was that the blocks and the 2×2-block matrix are represented in the same basis.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Karstadt and Schwartz computed in different bases and traded 3 additions for less expensive basis transformations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] They also proved that one cannot go below 12 additions per step using different bases.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] In subsequent work Beniamini et el. applied this base-change trick to more general decompositions than 2×2-block matrices and improved the leading constant for their run times.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] It is an open question in theoretical computer science how well Strassen's algorithm can be improved in terms of asymptotic complexity.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The *matrix multiplication exponent*, usually denoted $\omega$ , is the smallest real number for which any $n\times n$ matrix over a field can be multiplied together using $n^{\omega +o(1)}$ field operations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The current best bound on $\omega$ is $\omega <2.371339$ , by Alman, Duan, Williams, Xu, Xu, and Zhou.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This algorithm, like all other recent algorithms in this line of research, is a generalization of the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm, which was given by Don Coppersmith and Shmuel Winograd in 1990.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The conceptual idea of these algorithms is similar to Strassen's algorithm: a way is devised for multiplying two *k* × *k*-matrices with fewer than *k*3 multiplications, and this technique is applied recursively.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] However, the constant coefficient hidden by the big-O notation is so large that these algorithms are only worthwhile for matrices that are too large to handle on present-day computers.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Victor Pan proposed so-called feasible sub-cubic matrix multiplication algorithms with an exponent slightly above 2.77, but in return with a much smaller hidden constant coefficient.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Freivalds' algorithm is a simple Monte Carlo algorithm that, given matrices A, B and C, verifies in Θ(*n*2) time if *AB* = *C*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] In 2022, DeepMind introduced AlphaTensor, a neural network that used a single-player game analogy to invent thousands of matrix multiplication algorithms, including some previously discovered by humans and some that were not.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Operations were restricted to the non-commutative ground field (normal arithmetic) and finite field $\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ (mod 2 arithmetic).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The best "practical" (explicit low-rank decomposition of a matrix multiplication tensor) algorithm found ran in O(n2.778).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Finding low-rank decompositions of such tensors (and beyond) is NP-hard; optimal multiplication even for 3×3 matrices remains unknown, even in commutative field.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] On 4×4 matrices, AlphaTensor unexpectedly discovered a solution with 47 multiplication steps, an improvement over the 49 required with Strassen’s algorithm of 1969, albeit restricted to mod 2 arithmetic.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Similarly, AlphaTensor solved 5×5 matrices with 96 rather than Strassen's 98 steps.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Based on the surprising discovery that such improvements exist, other researchers were quickly able to find a similar independent 4×4 algorithm, and separately tweaked Deepmind's 96-step 5×5 algorithm down to 95 steps in mod 2 arithmetic and to 97 in normal arithmetic.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Some algorithms were completely new: for example, (4, 5, 5) was improved to 76 steps from a baseline of 80 in both normal and mod 2 arithmetic.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer algorithm sketched earlier can be parallelized in two ways for shared-memory multiprocessors.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] can be performed independently of each other, as can the four summations (although the algorithm needs to "join" the multiplications before doing the summations).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Here, *fork* is a keyword that signal a computation may be run in parallel with the rest of the function call, while *join* waits for all previously "forked" computations to complete. partition achieves its goal by pointer manipulation only.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This algorithm has a critical path length of Θ(log2 *n*) steps, meaning it takes that much time on an ideal machine with an infinite number of processors; therefore, it has a maximum possible speedup of Θ(*n*3/log2 *n*) on any real computer.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The algorithm isn't practical due to the communication cost inherent in moving data to and from the temporary matrix T, but a more practical variant achieves Θ(*n*2) speedup, without using a temporary matrix.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] On modern architectures with hierarchical memory, the cost of loading and storing input matrix elements tends to dominate the cost of arithmetic.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] On a single machine this is the amount of data transferred between RAM and cache, while on a distributed memory multi-node machine it is the amount transferred between nodes; in either case it is called the *communication bandwidth*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The naïve algorithm using three nested loops uses Ω(*n*3) communication bandwidth.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] Cannon's algorithm, also known as the *2D algorithm*, is a communication-avoiding algorithm that partitions each input matrix into a block matrix whose elements are submatrices of size √*M*/3 by √*M*/3, where *M* is the size of fast memory.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The naïve algorithm is then used over the block matrices, computing products of submatrices entirely in fast memory.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This reduces communication bandwidth to *O*(*n*3/√*M*), which is asymptotically optimal (for algorithms performing Ω(*n*3) computation).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This can be improved by the *3D algorithm,* which arranges the processors in a 3D cube mesh, assigning every product of two input submatrices to a single processor.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The result submatrices are then generated by performing a reduction over each row.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This algorithm transmits *O*(*n*2/*p*2/3) words per processor, which is asymptotically optimal.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] However, this requires replicating each input matrix element *p*1/3 times, and so requires a factor of *p*1/3 more memory than is needed to store the inputs.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] This algorithm can be combined with Strassen to further reduce runtime.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] "2.5D" algorithms provide a continuous tradeoff between memory usage and communication bandwidth.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] On modern distributed computing environments such as MapReduce, specialized multiplication algorithms have been developed.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] There are a variety of algorithms for multiplication on meshes.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] For multiplication of two *n*×*n* on a standard two-dimensional mesh using the 2D Cannon's algorithm, one can complete the multiplication in 3*n*-2 steps although this is reduced to half this number for repeated computations.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The standard array is inefficient because the data from the two matrices does not arrive simultaneously and it must be padded with zeroes.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The result is even faster on a two-layered cross-wired mesh, where only 2*n*-1 steps are needed.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The performance improves further for repeated computations leading to 100% efficiency.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] The cross-wired mesh array may be seen as a special case of a non-planar (i.e. multilayered) processing structure.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/matrix-multiplication-algorithm] In a 3D mesh with *n*3 processing elements, two matrices can be multiplied in ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ using the DNS algorithm.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] In computer science, a problem is said to have **optimal substructure** if an optimal solution can be constructed from optimal solutions of its subproblems.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] This property is used to determine the usefulness of greedy algorithms for a problem.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Typically, a greedy algorithm is used to solve a problem with optimal substructure if it can be proven by induction that this is optimal at each step.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Otherwise, provided the problem exhibits overlapping subproblems as well, divide-and-conquer methods or dynamic programming may be used.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] If there are no appropriate greedy algorithms and the problem fails to exhibit overlapping subproblems, often a lengthy but straightforward search of the solution space is the best alternative.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] This is an example of optimal substructure.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] The Principle of Optimality is used to derive the Bellman equation, which shows how the value of the problem starting from *t* is related to the value of the problem starting from *s*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Consider finding a shortest path for traveling between two cities by car, as illustrated in Figure 1.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Such an example is likely to exhibit optimal substructure.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] That is, if the shortest route from Seattle to Los Angeles passes through Portland and then Sacramento, then the shortest route from Portland to Los Angeles must pass through Sacramento too.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] That is, the problem of how to get from Portland to Los Angeles is nested inside the problem of how to get from Seattle to Los Angeles.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] As an example of a problem that is unlikely to exhibit optimal substructure, consider the problem of finding the cheapest airline ticket from Buenos Aires to Moscow.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] A slightly more formal definition of optimal substructure can be given.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Let a "problem" be a collection of "alternatives", and let each alternative have an associated cost, *c*(*a*).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] The task is to find a set of alternatives that minimizes *c*(*a*).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Suppose that the alternatives can be partitioned into subsets, i.e. each alternative belongs to only one subset.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] Suppose each subset has its own cost function.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] The minima of each of these cost functions can be found, as can the minima of the global cost function, *restricted to the same subsets*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] If these minima match for each subset, then it's almost obvious that a global minimum can be picked not out of the full set of alternatives, but out of only the set that consists of the minima of the smaller, local cost functions we have defined.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/optimal-substructure] If minimizing the local functions is a problem of "lower order", and (specifically) if, after a finite number of these reductions, the problem becomes trivial, then the problem has an optimal substructure.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:matrix-chain-multiplication/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
